<section class="section section--alt" id="recon-multi-account-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why this matters</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Why every account needs reconciling, not just checking.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Reconciliation is the monthly act of matching what your books say against what an outside record &mdash; a bank statement, a card statement, a lender&rsquo;s balance, a processor&rsquo;s report &mdash; says actually happened. Reconcile the operating checking account and you&rsquo;ve verified one slice of the business. The problem is that money rarely lives in just one place: it sits on credit cards, against loans and lines of credit, and inside the <em>clearing</em> accounts that payment processors and QuickBooks use to hold funds in transit. Every one of those is an account whose balance ends up on your financial statements &mdash; and every one that goes unreconciled is a balance nobody has verified.</p>
      <p>That&rsquo;s why &ldquo;is the bank reconciled?&rdquo; is the wrong question on its own. A card with duplicate charges, a loan whose interest was never split from principal, or an Undeposited Funds account quietly double-counting income will leave the books looking balanced while the numbers are wrong. The fix isn&rsquo;t more effort on checking &mdash; it&rsquo;s widening the net to every account that holds or moves money, and reconciling them all on the same monthly rhythm. What reconciling <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix on its own is a backlog: months that never tied, or accounts never reconciled at all. That part is a file review and a cleanup before the routine can carry the books forward.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

